This implies \( c^2 < 40 \), so the roots are complex. The vertices of the quadrilateral \( \mathcal{Q} \) are \( z_1 \), \( z_2 \), \( \frac{1}{z_1} \), and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \). Using Vieta's formulas, \( z_1 + z_2 = c \) and \( z_1 z_2 = 10 \). Let \( z_1 = a + bi \) and \( z_2 = a - bi \). Then \( a = \frac{c}{2} \) and \( a^2 + b^2 = 10 \). The modulus of \( z_1 \) is \( \sqrt{10} \), so \( \frac{1}{z_1} \) and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \) have modulus \( \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \). The coordinates of the vertices are: - \( z_1 = \left( \frac{c}{2}, \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \right) \) - \( z_2 = \left( \frac{c}{2}, -\sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \right) \) - \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \left( \frac{c}{20}, -\frac{\sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}}}{10} \right) \) - \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \left( \frac{c}{20}, \frac{\sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}}}{10} \right) \) Using the shoelace formula to find the area of the quadrilateral, we calculate: \[ \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \left| -c \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} + \frac{c}{100} \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \right| = \frac{99c}{200} \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \] To maximize this area, we take the derivative with respect to \( c \) and set it to zero: \[ \frac{d}{dc} \left( \frac{99c}{200} \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \right) = \frac{99}{200} \left( \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} - \frac{c^2}{4} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}}} \right) = 0 \] Solving \( 10 - \frac{c^2}{2} = 0 \) gives \( c^2 = 20 \), so \( c = \sqrt{20} \). Thus, \( m = 20 \). The value of \( m \) is \(\boxed{20}\).
